Below is a step-by-step outline of the reasoning used to arrive at the final rocket design. After this reasoning, you will find the “config” dictionary in the exact format required, containing no extraneous Python code.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REASONING FOR DESIGN CHOICES
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1) Motor Selection
   • Goal Apogee ~ 3048 m (10,000 ft).  
   • Smaller motors tend to be more cost-effective; huge motors (like “O” impulses) would be expensive and likely overshoot.  
   • “AeroTechK700W” provides 2249 Ns total impulse. With a modest total rocket mass (around 3.5–4 kg), this yields enough delta-v margin to reach ~3048 m without excessive overshoot.  
   • It is larger than a small H or K160 motor but still significantly more cost-friendly than the big M/O motors and should comfortably reach the target apogee.

2) Overall Dimensions and Materials
   • Motor radius is 27 mm → Rocket body radius must exceed 0.027 m. A 0.05 m body radius (50 mm) is chosen as a common mid-power dimension.  
   • Body length of ~1.4 m is a typical proportion for a rocket of this impulse range.  
   • Fiberglass is chosen for body material for a good balance of durability, weight, and cost (carbon_fiber might be lighter but is generally more expensive). A wall thickness of 3 mm is enough for structural integrity at these sizes.

3) Nose Cone
   • Ogive shape is commonly used due to good aerodynamic performance.  
   • A 0.25 m length balances stability, drag, and manufacturing complexity.  
   • Same fiberglass material keeps manufacturing simpler.

4) Fin Design
   • Three fins (rather than four) to reduce drag and cost, while still ensuring stable flight.  
   • Root chord 0.15 m and tip chord 0.07 m with a 0.12 m span is sufficient for aerodynamic stability.  
   • Zero cant angle helps keep the rocket from spinning excessively, minimizing horizontal drift.  
   • Fiberglass fins at 3 mm thickness for robustness.

5) Tail Section
   • Small tail segment (length 0.1 m) to help with motor integration and to ensure no geometry errors.  
   • The top radius equals the main body radius (0.05 m), and bottom radius is slightly larger (0.06 m). This satisfies the requirement that top and bottom radius not be identical, and helps with motor exhaust flow.  
   • Tail is also fiberglass for simplicity.

6) Parachute Sizing
   • We aim for <5 m/s landing speed. Rough drag-area calculations showed a main parachute Cd·Area (cd_s) around 2.5 for a ~4 kg rocket to achieve ~5 m/s.  
   • A smaller drogue chute (cd_s = 0.2) is included for controlled descent until main deployment.

7) Launch Configuration
   • Rail length of 2.0 m is reasonable for stability before the rocket leaves the rail.  
   • An inclination of 85° and heading of 90° (pointing slightly east) can partially counter winds from the east (to reduce net horizontal drift).

8) Payload
   • A small 0.5 kg payload located 0.7 m from the rocket’s center helps ensure stable CG placement without drastically affecting total mass.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINAL DESIGN (“config” DICTIONARY)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Below is a step-by-step outline of the reasoning used to arrive at an improved rocket design over the previous attempt, aiming to get closer to the 3048 m apogee while maintaining safety and minimizing cost. After these detailed considerations, you will find the final “config” dictionary in the requested format, containing no extraneous Python code.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1) Why We Needed a Change
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
The previous design with the AeroTechK700W motor only reached about 2651 m (roughly 13% under the 3048 m goal). To get closer to 3048 m without overshooting too much (which could risk structural stress or higher cost), we decided to lower overall rocket mass (so the same motor can accelerate it more efficiently) while still remaining stable.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2) Motor Selection
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• We keep the AeroTechK700W motor because it already provides decent thrust and total impulse (2249 Ns).  
• Larger motors (like M- or O-class) would be more expensive and could far overshoot the target, which might reduce score if the rocket drifts too far or if cost is too high.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3) Reducing Mass While Preserving Structure
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• The rocket body is shortened to 1.2 m (compared to 1.4 m before) to lighten the vehicle and reduce material cost.  
• The radius is reduced to 0.045 m, still larger than the motor’s ~0.027 m radius.  
• Wall thickness is reduced from 3 mm to 2 mm to save weight, but fiberglass still provides enough strength.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
4) Nose Cone
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• We use an ogive nose cone for low drag.  
• A length of 0.22 m helps maintain a good aerodynamic profile without adding excess mass.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5) Fin Design
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Three fins (fewer fins reduce mass and drag).  
• Balsa wood is chosen because it is cheaper and lighter than fiberglass or carbon fiber, reducing overall mass further.  
• Dimensions (root chord 0.14 m, tip chord 0.06 m, span 0.11 m, thickness 0.002 m) provide adequate stability at transonic speeds typical of K-impulse rockets.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6) Tail Section
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• A short tail (0.08 m) ensures stable motor mounting and transitions flow from the rocket to the nozzle exhaust area.  
• The top radius matches the body (0.045 m) and expands slightly to a bottom radius of 0.055 m, satisfying the requirement that top and bottom radii not be the same.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7) Parachutes
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Using a main parachute Cd·S of 2.3 helps limit descent speed to near or below 5 m/s for a ~3.5 – 4 kg rocket.  
• A small drogue chute (Cd·S = 0.2) stabilizes descent prior to main deployment.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
8) Launch Configuration & Wind Considerations
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• The rail length is 2.0 m, allowing the rocket to reach stable velocity before leaving the rail.  
• We slightly tilt (88 ° inclination) and set heading due west (270 °) to counter a prevailing wind from the east, helping reduce horizontal drift.  

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
9) Payload
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• A 0.6 kg payload is included at 0.6 m from the rocket’s center, ensuring the center of gravity remains sufficiently fore of the center of pressure, while still meeting the mission’s needs.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1) Understanding Previous Attempts
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Attempts 2 and 3 came very close to the target apogee (3080 m and 3055 m respectively) but failed structurally.  
• A key detail: the AeroTechK700W motor has a 54 mm case radius (0.054 m). Several earlier designs had a rocket body radius less than 0.054 m, which violates the requirement that the body radius must be greater than the motor radius. This can cause design-rule check (DRC) failures and structural issues in the simulation.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2) New Approach to Ensure Structural Integrity
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Increase rocket body radius to 0.06 m (60 mm), comfortably above the 54 mm motor radius requirement and providing extra internal space/strength margin.  
• Keep overall rocket length moderate (1.3 m), retaining enough volume while limiting weight.  
• Use a material stronger than balsa or thin fiberglass (such as “composite”) for both body and fins, and keep a reasonable thickness (3 mm) to handle higher dynamic pressures.  
• Keep the motor choice as AeroTechK700W, as it provides enough total impulse (~2249 Ns) to get us near 3048 m apogee without the excessive cost or drift of an M- or O-class motor.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3) Nose Cone
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Use an ogive shape for low drag.  
• Length of 0.25 m for aerodynamic efficiency without adding unnecessary mass.  
• Same composite material for simplicity and strength consistency.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
4) Fin Design
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Three fins for balanced stability and lower drag/cost than four.  
• Composite material at 3 mm thickness for improved structural margin.  
• The same approximate planform (root chord ~0.14 m, tip chord ~0.06 m, span ~0.11 m) aligns with stable flight from earlier attempts.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5) Tail Section
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Length of 0.1 m, matching the body’s 0.06 m top radius and tapering slightly to 0.065 m. Ensures top and bottom radii are not equal (meets DRC rules).  
• Composite material, same thickness, to avoid a structural weak point.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6) Parachutes
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Main parachute Cd·S of 2.4 for ≤ 5 m/s landing on a ~4 kg rocket.  
• Small drogue parachute (Cd·S = 0.2) ensures a stable descent from apogee until main deployment.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7) Launch Configuration & Wind
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Launch rail length of 2.2 m to allow the rocket more time to reach a stable velocity before leaving the rail.  
• 88 ° inclination (near-vertical) and a heading of 270 ° west to counter moderate easterly winds.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
8) Payload
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• 0.65 kg mass at 0.6 m from the rocket center.  
• This minor mass helps shift the CG forward but still keeps overall mass manageable for the K700.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REASONING & DESIGN CHOICES
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1) Why the K700 Motor
• The AeroTechK700W supplies ~2249 Ns of total impulse.  
• That proved sufficient in earlier attempts to reach near 3048 m, if the rocket was not too heavy.  
• Larger motors (e.g., “M” or “O” class) would be more expensive and risk overshooting the target, while smaller motors would not provide enough impulse.  

2) Body Radius Must Be Greater Than 54 mm
• A key DRC rule is that the rocket body radius must exceed the motor’s 54 mm.  
• Previous attempts with < 0.054 m body radius were invalid or experienced structural failures in the simulator.  
• Thus, we choose a 0.055 m rocket body radius to pass the motor fit requirement while still keeping diameter modest.

3) Balancing Structural Integrity and Mass
• Attempt 4 was structurally sound (no failure) but reached only ~2129 m, suggesting it was too heavy or had too much drag.  
• To reduce mass and keep decent strength, we use fiberglass (generally cheaper and lighter than some “composite” blends) with 2 mm thickness on the main body.  
• Fins also made of fiberglass at 2 mm thickness to reduce weight versus thicker or denser materials.

4) Nose Cone
• An ogive shape (0.25 m length) remains a good aerodynamic choice.  
• Same fiberglass material (2 mm wall) to maintain uniform manufacturing and cost savings.

5) Fin Geometry
• Three fins (root chord 0.14 m, tip chord 0.06 m, span 0.11 m) provide adequate stability with lower drag and cost than four fins.  
• Zero cant angle to reduce roll and horizontal drift.  
• Fiberglass at 0.002 m thickness is chosen to improve strength without excessive weight or cost.

6) Tail Section
• A short tail (0.10 m length) helps transition from the main body to the motor nozzle area.  
• Top radius = 0.055 m and bottom radius = 0.06 m, ensuring they are not identical (avoiding DRC errors).  
• Fiberglass again for consistency and cost considerations.

7) Parachutes
• Main chute Cd·S = 2.4 to achieve ~5 m/s or lower landing speed if the rocket mass is in the 3.5–4.5 kg range.  
• Drogue chute Cd·S = 0.2 to stabilize descent immediately after apogee.

8) Launch Setup & Wind
• Launch rail length of 2.2 m, giving the rocket more distance to reach safe speed off the rail.  
• Inclination of 88 ° (close to vertical) and heading of 270 ° (west) to counter moderate easterly winds of ~5 m/s.

9) Payload
• A 0.6 kg mass at 0.65 m from the rocket center helps set the center of gravity forward.  
• Keeps the total launch mass from becoming too high while still carrying a practical payload.

Below is a step-by-step summary of the reasoning used to create an improved design, followed by the final “config” dictionary in the required format. No extra Python code is included.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1) Why Switch to an M-Class Motor?
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Repeated attempts with the AeroTech K700W (~2249 Ns) either fell short of 3048 m or had structural issues once the rocket body was made large enough to accommodate the 54 mm motor requirement.  
• Moving up to the Pro75 M1670 (~6023 Ns) provides more total impulse and allows designing a sturdier, larger rocket that won’t have to be excessively light or thin to reach 3048 m.  
• Even though the M motor is more powerful and potentially more expensive, it can be balanced against an increased rocket mass to aim near 3048 m apogee while maintaining structural integrity.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2) Body Diameter and Length
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• The Pro75 M1670 has a 75 mm radius requirement, so the rocket body radius must exceed 0.075 m.  
• Chosen radius: 0.08 m (80 mm), giving a modest margin for motor fit plus space for structural thickness.  
• Body length of 2.2 m accommodates this larger motor and payload while avoiding an overly tall airframe that adds weight and cost.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3) Structural Material and Thickness
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Fiberglass is chosen for both the airframe and fins: relatively cost-effective and durable.  
• A 4 mm (0.004 m) wall thickness provides sufficient strength to handle the higher thrust and dynamic pressures from an M-class motor.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
4) Nose Cone
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Ogive shape, length = 0.3 m, for low drag and good aerodynamic performance.  
• Same fiberglass material and thickness for uniformity.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5) Fin Design
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Four fins for enhanced stability with higher thrust loads.  
• Generous fin area (root chord 0.18 m, tip chord 0.08 m, span 0.15 m) helps maintain stable flight.  
• Fiberglass at 4 mm thickness prevents flutter or structural failure.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6) Tail Section
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• 0.2 m length to transition smoothly from body diameter to the motor nozzle region.  
• Top radius = 0.08 m, bottom radius = 0.09 m (they cannot be equal).  
• Fiberglass to match the rest of the rocket.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7) Parachutes
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
